org.jlinalg.polynomial
Class Polynomial<BASE extends IRingElement>

java.lang.Object
  org.jlinalg.RingElement
      org.jlinalg.polynomial.Polynomial<BASE>
Type Parameters:
BASE - The type for the domain of the polynomials' coefficients.
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<IRingElement>, IRingElement
public class Polynomial<BASE extends IRingElement>
extends RingElement
implements IRingElement

A class of polynomials. This constructor of class requires that a the factory of a base type is created first and then passed to the constructor. Alternatively, the factory can be used. For example, the following creates a factory for polynomials for a rational domain: 

 PolynomialFactory<Rational>== PolynomialFactory.getFactory(Rational.FACTORY);
Then, the polynomial "1+2*x^2+2*x^3" can be created as follows: 
 Map<Integer, Rational> coeff1 = new HashMap<Integer, Rational>();
 coeff1.put(0, new Rational(1));
 coeff1.put(1, new Rational(2));
 coeff1.put(2, new Rational(3));
 Polynomial<Rational> polynomial = rationalPolyFactory.get(coeff1);

Author:
Andreas Keilhauer, Georg Thimm

norm

public Polynomial<BASE> norm()
It can be shown that the degree of a polynomial over a field satisfies all of the requirements of a norm function in the euclidean domain. That is, given two polynomials f(x) and g(x), the degree of the product f(x)ï¿½g(x) must be larger than both the degrees of f and g individually. In fact, something stronger holds: degree( f(x) * g(x) ) = degree(f(x)) + degree(g(x))

Specified by:
norm in interface IRingElement
Overrides:
norm in class RingElement
Returns:
the degree of this polynomial as a polynomial (of degree 0)
